03783nmm a2200589Ia 9780801459832DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20102011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014598327 a10.7591/97808014598322doi  a(DE-B1597)503384  a(OCoLC)1059297257  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUB41704a306.2709731 aKrebs, Ronald R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFighting for Rights :bMilitary Service and the Politics of Citizenship /cRonald R. Krebs. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 list, 7 line figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeaders around the globe have long turned to the armed forces as a "school for the nation." Debates over who serves continue to arouse passion today because the military's participation policies are seen as shaping politics beyond the military, specifically the politics of identity and citizenship. Yet how and when do these policies transform patterns of citizenship? Military service, Ronald R. Krebs argues, can play a critical role in bolstering minorities' efforts to grasp full and unfettered rights. Minority groups have at times effectively contrasted their people's battlefield sacrifices to the reality of inequity, compelling state leaders to concede to their claims. At the same time, military service can shape when, for what, and how minorities have engaged in political activism in the quest for meaningful citizenship. Employing a range of rich primary materials, Krebs shows how the military's participation policies shaped Arab citizens' struggles for first-class citizenship in Israel from independence to the mid-1980s and African Americans' quest for civil rights, from World War I to the Korean War. Fighting for Rights helps us make sense of contemporary debates over gays in the military and over the virtues and dangers of liberal and communitarian visions for society. It suggests that rhetoric is more than just a weapon of the weak, that it is essential to political exchange, and that politics rests on a dual foundation of rationality and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil-military relationszIsrael. 0aCivil-military relationszUnited States. 0aSociology, MilitaryzIsrael. 0aSociology, MilitaryzUnited States. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145983240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801459832423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801459832/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles